Snow¶

xarray¶

By: Victor Cornejo

Introduction¶

In this project I explored worldwide snow levels using the xarray package, uncovering interesting trends in snow density over time.

ERA5 Snow Cover¶

In this part of the task, I explored worldwide snow accumulation trends from the ERA5 dataset. More specifically, I wanted to look at the yearly minimum and maximum snow accumulation levels, and see if there were any interesting trends. I used xarray to accomplish this part.

With xarray is also nice in that, if I wanted to average the snow density measurements across all time and plot the aggregate values by spatial location, I could do this in two lines of code.

In [6]:
# run this cell
mean_map = ds.mean("time")  # takes the mean across all variables in ds
mean_map.snow_density.plot(); # extract snow_density DataArray, then plot
In [7]:
snow.sel(time='1980-02').plot();
In [8]:
snow.sel(time='1980-08').plot();

I could notice how these plots made a lot of sense: snow cover is higher in the Northern hemisphere during winter time, and when summer comes around, that snow melts. However, at the same time, winter arrives in the Southern hemisphere, and so snow appears on mountains in South America and New Zealand.

I then continued analyzing the data, with the ultimate goal of understanding and displaying trends of snow accumulation over the years using xarray.

In both the northern and southern hemispheres, I made lineplots showing the average snow density (averaged across all locations in the respective hemisphere) on the y-axis and the date/time on the x-axis. I also created xarray.DataArray objects containing this spatially-aggregated data, one for each hemisphere.

In [9]:
t_snow_north = snow.sel(latitude=slice(-90,90)).mean(dim=['latitude', 'longitude'])
t_snow_north.plot();
In [10]:
t_snow_south = snow.sel(latitude=slice(0,90)).mean(dim=['latitude', 'longitude'])
t_snow_south.plot();

For each hemisphere, we observe clear cycles in average snow accumulation over time, which makes sense because of seasonal temperature changes. However, the plots above are a little bit busy. For this part, I made a similar plot, but only showing the average snow density measurements for the northern hemisphere in the year 1979.

In [11]:
t_snow_north.sel(time='1979').plot();

Now that I had a sense of seasonal and yearly change in snow accumulation in both hemispheres, I worked to use xarray to extract the yearly maxima and minima to get a sense of how these levels are changing over time.

For this part, I filled in the extract_peaks function such that, if I plugged in an xarray.DataArray containing average snow density measurements for each hemisphere over time, I'd return a pandas.DataFrame.

When constructing the extract_peaks function, I thought about what information I wanted my DataFrame to contain, what information my xarray.DataArray objects contained already, and how I could write code to get the desired output.

So:

  1. First, I wanted to extract the years from the data and iterate over them using range
  2. When iterating over the years, for each year, I extracted the maximum and minimum snow accumulation measurements, as well as the day of year and dates that those measurements occured on. Amplitude was computed by taking the difference between a year's max and min snow accumulation levels, and all of this information will be stored in an array called vals.
  3. I created peaks as an array consisting of all of the information in vals, plus any other columns I asked for that was not already in vals.

      def extract_peaks(snow_data):
    vals = []
    years = snow_data.time.dt.year.values
    peaks = []
    for year in set(years):
        min_date = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).idxmin()
        max_date = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).idxmax()
        min_dayofyear = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).idxmin().dt.dayofyear.values.item()
        max_dayofyear = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).idxmax().dt.dayofyear.values.item()
        min_snow = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).min().values.item()
        max_snow = snow_data.sel(time=str(year)).max().values.item()
        amplitude = max_snow - min_snow
        vals = [year, min_date, max_date, min_dayofyear, max_dayofyear, min_snow, max_snow, amplitude]
        peaks.append(vals)

    snow_peaks = pd.DataFrame(peaks, 
                              columns = ['year', 'min_date', 'max_date',
                                         'min_dayofyear', 'max_dayofyear',
                                         'min_snow', 'max_snow', 'amplitude'])

    return snow_peaks

peaks_north = extract_peaks(t_snow_north)
